  "content": {
    "problemStatement": "Given **N** points on a 2D plane and an integer **K**, choose 3 distinct points so that the area of the triangle whose vertices are the chosen points does not exceed **K**/2. If there are multiple such triangles, among all possible triangles choose the one which has maximum area.",
    "constraints": [
      "3 ≤ **N** ≤ 3000",
      "1 ≤ **K** ≤ 1018",
      "1 ≤ **Xi**,**Yi** ≤ 109",
      "No two points will have same coordinates",
      "No three points will be collinear",
      "&nbsp;",
      "Example 1**Input:**",
      "4 7",
      "1 1",
      "5 1",
      "3 3",
      "3 2",
      "**Output:**",
      "4",
      "Example 2**Input:**",
      "3 7",
      "1 1",
      "4 1",
      "1 4",
      "**Output:**",
      "-1",
      "Example 3**Input:**",
      "7 1234567890123",
      "1234567 7654321",
      "1111111 2222222",
      "1212121 2323232",
      "3333333 1122334",
      "9292929 2929292",
      "1234456 5654645",
      "5435733 2342134",
      "**Output:**",
      "755024295480",
      "&nbsp;",
      "Explanation**Example case 1.** There are 4 triangles in total, and their areas are: 1, 1, 2 and 4. The ones which does not exceed 7/2 are 1, 1 and 2 so the biggest area is 2, and since we are required to multiply the area by 2 before outputting it, it becomes 4.",
      "**Example case 2.** The only triangle has an area equal to 9/2, which is more than 7/2. So the answer is -1."
    ],
    "inputFormat": "First line contains two integers **N** and **K**.\n\n\nEach of the next **N** lines contains two integers **Xi** and **Yi**, denoting the coordinates of the i-th point.",
    "outputFormat": "Output a single integer, the maximum area of a triangle which does not exceed **K**/2,  multiplied by 2. If there's no valid triangle output -1 instead.",
